@node Introduction "MusicBugs: Introduction"

                              ---Introduction---

   What The Hell Is This????

   Good question. As i'm not really sure 8)  I saw something like this a few
   years ago on a program about wierd ideas for computers on BBC2. Basically
   you have these little bug things that walk aroung the screen, and when
   they walk over a colour, they play a note, with a pitch that depends on
   the particular colour. You draw to the screen, so can create wierd beats
   and stuff. I had never seen a program like this on Amiga (or any computer)
   before, so i decided to write it, to add variety to the Amiga's sofware
   resources.

@endnode




@node Requirements "MusicBugs Requirements"

                              ---Requirements---

   *An AGA Amiga.
   *A Mouse
   *Peferably a HD to run it from. It is possible to run it from disk, but
     it needs "mathtrans.library" in a "Libs" drawer. Besides, everyone's
     got a HD now right?????

@endnode





@node Usage "MusicBugs: Usage"
                                 ---Usage---

     Using MusicBugs is quite straight forward really. Once loaded, and the
   MusicBugs title screen has appeared, then just click the LMB. Now you
   should see a black screen with a palette bar along the bottom, and
   four different coloured little bugs walking around. The bugs do not alter
   the direction they walk in, unless you use a Command Colour, such as White
   or Grey. Simply click on a Pitch colour (Purple to Yellow), and draw with
   the LMB. When a bug walks over a colour, it will play it's instrument at
   a pitch determined by the colour it's walked over. Pressing Esc key quits
   MusicBugs.

     Each bug has it's own instrument or sample to play. These can be changed
   by clicking the RMB. this takes you to the Assign Instruments screen. Here
   clicking the RMB will go to another option, while the LMB will cycle
   through the available instruments. Clicking LMB on "Clear!" will clear the
   main screen of all drawing. Clicking on "Return" will return you to the
   main screen. The colour of the writing for the bugs, curresponds to the
   colour of the bug. The number at the bottom of the screen indicates how
   much Chip memory is left for more samples to be added.

     The "Samples" drawer contains the samples which can be used by the bugs.
   Only a MAXIMUM of 20 can be put in here, BUT if using big samples, memory
   restrictions may restrict the use further. Use the Chip Mem free at the
   bottom of the "Assign Instruments" screen to judge the amount of space left
   for more samples. To use your own samples, simply put them into the
   "Samples" drawer. You do NOT have to rename your samples to the ones already
   in there. The program should read the new sample names automatically. Also
   feel free to delete the sample already in there. It is VERY important that
   your samples are of the correct format, which is 8SVX IFF MONO. This should
   not really cause any problems as it is the standard for samples on Amiga.
   If you add samples and it starts crashing while loading and displaying the
   Jigsaw Design logo, then it's because of your dodgy samples.

@endnode





